### Composition vs Inheritance

React recommends using composition over inheritance to reuse code between components. Composition builds complex UIs by combining simpler components.

---

### Composition with Children

```jsx
function FancyBorder({ color, children }) {
  return (
    <div className={`border-${color}`}>
      {children}
    </div>
  );
}

function WelcomeDialog() {
  return (
    <FancyBorder color="blue">
      <h1>Welcome</h1>
      <p>Thank you for visiting</p>
    </FancyBorder>
  );
}
```

### Composition with Multiple Slots

```jsx
function SplitPane({ left, right }) {
  return (
    <div className="split-pane">
      <div className="left">{left}</div>
      <div className="right">{right}</div>
    </div>
  );
}

<SplitPane
  left={<Contacts />}
  right={<Chat />}
/>
```

### Specialization

```jsx
function Dialog({ title, message, children }) {
  return (
    <div className="dialog">
      <h2>{title}</h2>
      <p>{message}</p>
      {children}
    </div>
  );
}

function SignUpDialog() {
  return (
    <Dialog title="Sign Up" message="Create your account">
      <input placeholder="Email" />
      <button>Sign Up</button>
    </Dialog>
  );
}
```

| Approach | Use Case |
|----------|----------|
| Containment | Generic containers (modals, cards) |
| Specialization | Specific variants of a base component |
| Props | Passing configuration and data |
| Children | Rendering nested arbitrary content |

> **Key Point:** Class inheritance in React creates tight coupling and is rarely needed. Composition through children props, render props, or hooks provides more flexibility and cleaner separation of concerns.

codeExample:
function Card({ title, actions, children }) {
  return (
    <div className="card">
      <div className="card-header">
        <h3>{title}</h3>
        {actions}
      </div>
      <div className="card-body">
        {children}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

<Card
  title="User Profile"
  actions={<button>Edit</button>}
>
  <p>Name: John Doe</p>
  <p>Email: john@example.com</p>
</Card>
